subsection.p:
But if we wanted to actually have the computer find the 10,000th value via the recursive definition, Sage (computing via Python) can't even do it:


    %%time
    def recursive(x):
        if x == 0:
            return 1;
        elif x == 1:
            return 3;
        else:
            return recursive(x-2)

    print(recursive(10000))


    RuntimeError: maximum recursion depth exceeded while calling a Python object

statement.p:
A linear homogeneous recurrence relation of degree k with constant coefficients is a recurrence relation of the form
a_n = c_1 a_{n-1} + c_2a_{n-2} + \dots + c_k a_{n-k}
where c_1, c_2, \dots , c_k are real numbers with c_k \not=0.

If a_n = r^n is a solution to the recurrence relation, then we we can plug it in: 

   \displaystyle a_n &= c_1 a_{n-1} + c_2a_{n-2} + \dots + c_k a_{n-k} 
   \displaystyle r^n &= c_1 r^{n-1} + c_2r^{n-2} + \dots + c_k r^{n-k} 
   \text{ Divide both sides by } r^{n-k}

    \displaystyle r^k &= c_1 r^{k-1} + c_2r^{k-2} + \dots + c_k

  \displaystyle r^k - c_1 r^{k-1} - c_2r^{k-2} - \dots - c_k &= 0
